- Receiving feedback well is a learnable skill, not an inborn trait
    - The field has spent decades teaching givers how to push more skillfully, ignoring the receiver
    - Yet the receiver controls what they let in, how they make sense of it, and whether they change
    - Pushing harder rarely opens the door to genuine learning; the leverage is on the receiving side
    - Receiving well doesn't mean always taking the feedback
        - It means engaging skillfully, managing emotional triggers, sorting what is useful, and choosing whether and how to use what was offered
        - Sometimes receiving well means setting limits and saying no
    - The tension between learning and being accepted runs through every feedback conversation
        - We are wired to learn; we are also wired to want acceptance
        - The fact of feedback implies that how we are is not quite okay
        - This tension is not going away, but it can be managed
        - Naming both drives simultaneously is itself the first diagnostic move
    - The benefits of receiving well extend beyond the individual
        - Richer relationships, higher job satisfaction, faster adaptation in new roles, lower turnover
        - Seeking out negative feedback correlates with higher performance ratings
        - How leaders receive feedback sets the tone for organizational learning culture
        - How parents receive feedback teaches children how to handle their own setbacks
        - John Gottman: a person's willingness and ability to accept influence from their spouse is a key predictor of a healthy marriage
    - Feedback is any information you get about yourself
        - Annual performance reviews, climate surveys, the way your son's eyes light up when he spots you, your bum knee talking to you about your diminishing spryness
        - Feedback can be formal or informal, direct or implicit, blunt or baroque
        - The sweater that fits a size too small: is that feedback about the sweater, or about my weight, or about something else entirely?

- Three triggers that block feedback
    - Every difficult feedback reaction traces to one of three triggers
    - Identifying which trigger is firing — before applying any remedy — is the first move
    - Triggers can fire in combination; some feedback trips all three simultaneously
    - The trigger is not evidence about the feedback's content; it is a report about your nervous system and history

    - Truth triggers: the feedback seems wrong, unfair, or unhelpful
        - The wrong-spotting instinct
            - We listen with the question "what is wrong with this?" running in the background
            - We scan for the part that is inaccurate and use it to dismiss the whole
            - The 2+2=5 error: one wrong part discredits the rest, even when the rest is right
            - The different-planet error: we live in such different contexts that of course they see it wrong
            - The used-to-be-right error: this was accurate before, but things have changed
            - Paul: "I don't listen to feedback to accept or reject it, but first to understand it"
            - The upstream switch: catch the wrong-spotting instinct and shift to "what might be right?"
        - Feedback arrives as labels: spot the label
            - "Be more assertive," "be more strategic," "show more leadership" — high definition in the giver's head, almost no content in transit
            - Adrianna and Nicholas: he hears "be more assertive at work" and imagines one thing; she means something quite specific about particular situations
            - "Be more affectionate" has eight possible meanings; filling in your own produces a conversation that never touches what they actually meant
            - Your auto-fill replaces their meaning with your own definition
            - The move: resist the auto-fill; ask what they actually observed and what different behavior would look like
        - Separate data from interpretation
            - Feedback arrives packaged as a label or conclusion; the useful content is in the data and interpretation underneath
            - The coming-from move: what did they actually observe? What interpretation did they make of it?
            - Push past second-order interpretations offered as data: "you're never there for me" is an interpretation, not an observation
            - Nicholas pushing Adrianna: she needs to separate what he saw (she pushed her chair back when the client questioned her) from what he made of it (she seemed uncomfortable with confrontation)
            - The two-step: what did you see? What do you make of it?
        - Clarify where the feedback is going
            - Coaching: if I wanted to follow this, would I know how? What specifically would be different?
            - Evaluation: what are the consequences? What is still open? What do I need to do now?
            - The rip-cord questions: what exactly are you recommending? What happens if nothing changes?
            - The actionability test for coaching: could you make a movie of what "doing it differently" would look like?
        - When you have understood and still disagree: difference-spot-not-wrong-spot
            - Shift from "who is right?" to "what is different about our data?" and "what is different about our interpretations?"
            - Two common sources of interpretive difference
                - Different implicit rules: they think X is unprofessional; you think X is efficient
                - Heroes-and-villains framing: same behavior, different moral lens applied to it
            - Closing step: ask what's right — acknowledge what is valid before sitting with the disagreement
            - The "when-I-still-disagree" stance: be transparent about your reactions while staying open and curious
        - Blind spots: feedback that seems wrong but might be accurate
            - The gap between how we see ourselves and how others experience us
            - Three amplifiers of the gap
                - We judge ourselves by our intent; others judge us by our impact on them
                - We explain our behavior by situation; others attribute it to character
                - We focus on the feeling driving the behavior; others see only what leaks out
            - Behavioral blind spots: leaky face, leaky tone, leaky patterns
                - Your face communicates emotions you don't know you're having
                - Your tone carries what you thought you hid; others can often detect when someone is distorting, manufacturing, or withholding an emotion
                - Your patterns are invisible to you, obvious to people who interact with you regularly
            - Emotional math blind spots: we unconsciously add or subtract from others' emotional scores
            - Situation-vs-character blind spots: we explain our own behavior by situation, attribute theirs to character
            - Use your own reaction as a blind spot signal
                - When the case you build against the giver is strong, ask: might the feedback be in my blind spot?
                - "Looking harder" at feedback you think is wrong produces more of the same dismissal verdict; substituting the blind-spot question is the inversion
            - Ask how you're getting in your own way
                - Replace "any feedback?" with "what's one thing you see me doing that gets in my own way?"
                - This grants permission to be candid and narrows to behavior with observable impact
            - Know which kind of mirror you need
                - Honest mirror: tell me what you actually observe, even if it's hard to hear
                - Supportive mirror: help me feel okay about this situation
                - Name the kind out loud before asking; the default implicit ask is for a supportive mirror
                - The problem is conflation, not choosing one type
            - Look for pattern not counterexample
                - Look for consistency across time and source, not the exception that dismisses
                - Richard's three girlfriends all said he was emotionally distant; he started paying attention the third time
                - Me+Everybody patterns: when the same feedback recurs across relationships, changing yourself can improve multiple systems simultaneously
            - Separate impact from intent
                - The asymmetry: we project our own impact onto others as evidence of their intentions
                - Three amplifiers that widen the intent-impact gap: emotional math, situation vs. character, impact vs. intent itself
                - Inside-out change: if the underlying feeling doesn't change, the surface behavior change leaks

    - Relationship triggers: the who and how trip you regardless of the what
        - The six trigger families
            - Skill/judgment: you have no standing to raise this; you did it wrong (timing, tone, place)
            - Credibility: you don't know what you're talking about on this subject
            - Trust: your motives are suspect; this isn't for my benefit
            - Appreciation: after all I've done, this is what I get back?
            - Autonomy: this is mine to decide; you don't get to weigh in here
            - Acceptance: you're asking me to be a fundamentally different person, not adjust a behavior
        - The switchtrack: the conversation quietly splits into two topics
            - You and the giver are each on a different topic while using the same words
            - Louie and Kim: she gives him feedback about the roses she doesn't like (her topic: does he listen to her?); he hears a critique of his effort (his topic: does she appreciate him?)
            - The trap: your second topic may be at least as important as the first; but staying on only your track means the original feedback goes nowhere; each of you ends up giving feedback neither of you is receiving
            - Both topics can be true simultaneously; both deserve attention
            - Silent switchtrack: you address the feedback on the surface; in your head you've already switched to your topic; you never raise it; you triangulate to a third party instead
            - Signpost and track each topic
                - Step outside the conversation; name both topics out loud
                - Ella and her mother: "Mom, I hear that you're saying I didn't get you a thank-you gift after the vacation. I want to talk about that. I also want to talk about something I've been sitting on — feeling like I can never get anything right with you. Can we do both?"
                - Propose a sequence: default to the giver's topic first unless your trigger is too loud to hear past; the two-factor rule
        - Listen for the issue beneath the coaching
            - Inverse case: the giver has packaged a relationship concern as coaching
            - The surface topic (the advice) is not the real one (the relationship concern)
            - The mother who gives her daughter advice about her marriage: the coaching is packaging for a worry that she's losing connection with her daughter
            - Four "might mean" diagnostic pairs: "you should call more often" might mean "I miss you"; "you should be more decisive" might mean "I feel anxious when things are uncertain"
            - The check-question: "Are we on the same track? What is the real topic here?"
            - "What are you worried about?" as the probe that surfaces the actual concern
        - The relationship system: see the system, not just the individual
            - Feedback in a relationship is rarely about you alone; it is about the dynamic between you
            - One step back: you+me intersections
                - What is the specific you-and-me combination of tendencies that produces the spiral?
                - Sandy's comfort-spending and Gil's monitoring-panic each amplify the other's coping
                - Neither is wrong alone; together they generate the problem
                - The snoring husband and the sensitive wife: each sees the other's contribution clearly and not their own; both are required to produce the problem
                - Systems Insight 1: each of us is part of the problem; Systems Insight 2: each of us sees only the other's contribution
                - We don't see our own system patterns, though people outside can spot them easily: the father-in-law who sees that the children have learned Mom doesn't "mean it" until she yells
            - Two steps back: role clashes and accidental adversaries
                - Some roles create structural conflict regardless of personality: compliance and trading, Sales and Legal, surgeons and anesthesiologists, HR and everyone
                - "Accidental adversaries": each attributes the problem to the other's character; the true culprit is the structure of their roles
            - Three steps back: the big picture
                - Other players, physical environment, timing and decision-making, policies, coping strategies
                - The Benny/Alice/Vince/board chain: Benny's late delivery is the presenting problem; the board's habit of changing requirements, Alice's failure to pass those changes on, and the absence of honest accounting of how changes affect timelines are the structural contributors
                - "Fixes that fail": solutions aimed at one component of the system that generate new problems elsewhere
            - Use the system to support change, not thwart it
                - Once you see the system's contours, make changes that don't require personality change: shift roles, change processes, change the environment
                - Me+Everybody patterns: when one person changes, multiple systems improve simultaneously
        - Shifting and absorbing: two dysfunctional accountability patterns
            - Absorbers: accept all responsibility quickly; cut conversations short; don't explore the system; let others off the hook; resentment builds privately
                - In abusive relationships: the feedback the abuser gives ("you provoked me") may accurately describe the absorber's contribution while completely omitting the harm being done
            - Shifters: deflect all blame to external causes; victim stance; feedback bounces off; feel perpetually victimized and powerless
                - If I contribute to my own problems, there are things I have the power to change; the shifter's stance removes that power
            - Interrupt the pattern: once named, it can be challenged
        - Take responsibility first, then introduce the system
            - Two messages: "I take responsibility for my part" AND "we are both contributing"
            - Message one must be settled before message two is raised
            - If message two arrives before message one is settled, the giver reads it as sophisticated deflection
            - Avoid the phrase "relationship system" altogether — it signals theory rather than honesty
            - Gauge readiness: if the giver is still visibly angry or has not registered message one, message two should wait
        - Ask what would help you change
            - When the giver is stuck in "this is all about you" and can't hear the system: describe what they could do differently that would help you change
            - Frame it as serving your change, not as critique of them — and it must be genuine
            - Gil's script to Sandy: "I have the strongest reaction to being surprised, because it makes me panic about where else you might be spending. I know I'm overreacting sometimes and I'm working on that. It would help me if you would be willing to be upfront with me about the Grape-Nuts and the mochaccino mini-vacations, and we can budget for them together."

    - Identity triggers: what this feedback says about who I am
        - Wiring: why people metabolize feedback so differently
            - Three variables that differ enormously across individuals
            - Baseline
                - The default level of well-being you return to after positive and negative events
                - Happiness is one of the most heritable aspects of personality; about 50% of variance is genetic
                - People with lower baselines get less boost from positive feedback and are hit harder by negative
                - Krista has a high baseline: criticism doesn't stick; Alita has a lower baseline: the critical comments land hard and persist
                - Lottery winners return to approximately their prior happiness level within a year
            - Swing: how far up or down you move from baseline
                - Some people swing wide in response to even minor inputs; others remain in a narrow band
                - High-reactive infants grow into high-reactive adults; differences appear to be present from birth
                - Eliza is frantic from the same client message that Jeron reads as "a bit more work"
                - Brain imaging: high-reactive infants showed greater thickness in right ventromedial prefrontal cortex as adults
            - Sustain and recovery: how long you ride the boost and how quickly you return
                - Recovery time differs by up to 3,000 percent across individuals
                - The left side of the prefrontal cortex exerts a calming influence on the amygdala; "cortical lefties" recover faster
                - People with more connections between the left prefrontal cortex and the amygdala effectively have a superhighway for delivering reassuring signals
                - Alita: positive feedback evaporates in minutes; negative comments land like a sledgehammer and stick
                - Krista: fast recovery; negative feedback doesn't adequately catch her attention — a different challenge
                - You can extend positive sustain by deliberately recalling positive feedback
            - Bad is stronger than good: the amygdala has a direct connection to the panic system for threats, but no equivalent green alert for opportunities
                - Jonathan Haidt: responses to threats are faster, stronger, and harder to inhibit than responses to opportunities
                - One criticism buried in four hundred compliments is what lingers; the brain has no equivalent "green alert"
            - The liberation: wiring is not destiny, not judgment-worthy, not fixed
                - Like your naturally curly hair or flat feet, your wiring is not more blame-worthy than whether your second toe is longer than the first
                - Practices like meditation, serving others, and exercise can raise your baseline over time
                - The 50-40-10 formula: about 50% of happiness is wired in; 40% is how you interpret and respond to events; 10% is circumstances
                - The 40% is the zone you can actually work on
        - How emotions distort our stories about feedback
            - Our stories are made of thoughts and feelings simultaneously — like a movie and its soundtrack
            - When we're absorbed in a good movie, we don't notice the music; when things go wrong, we need to slow down and observe the effect our emotions are having on how we tell the story
            - Two directions of causality: feelings color stories AND stories generate feelings
            - The Google bias: when you feel bad, you effectively search for "things that are wrong with me"
                - Returns 8.4 million examples; you can't recall a single thing you've ever done right
                - Marc: "The feedback could be small, but if I'm feeling vulnerable, it's as if I fall through the floor, plunged into the basement where all the things I've ever regretted are collected. When I'm not in the basement I literally don't think about it. But when I'm there, it's the only reality."
            - Flooding: feedback on one specific thing floods your general self-image
                - "I sing off key" becomes "I can't do anything right"; "my colleague has a concern" becomes "everybody on the team hates me"
                - Flooding also drowns any positive attributes that might provide balance
            - Forever bias and snowballing: bad feelings projected forward as permanent; a chain of imagined disasters
                - "I feel precisely this humiliated up to the moment of my death"
                - "I had mayonnaise on my cheek during the date" becomes "I will die alone"
                - What's amazing about these distortions is how real they appear from inside them
        - Dismantling distortions: five strategies
            - Strategy 1: know your feedback footprint; be prepared and mindful
                - Your footprint: Bryan blames others; Claire switchtracks; Anu cries; Alfie apologizes; Mick chatters; Hester goes silent; Fergie agrees while quietly resolving never to change; Reynolds lawyers up emotionally; Jody becomes awkwardly friendly
                - Know your footprint so you can name your reaction to yourself in the moment
                - Seth working to improve: "Once I think 'yep, this is the part where I have my overreactions,' I actually start to calm down." Self-observation activates the left prefrontal cortex.
                - Inoculation: before a high-stakes conversation, imagine the worst outcome; try it on emotionally; reason through what you would do if it arrived
                    - Benefits: acts as inoculation (familiar threat is less shocking); gives you a chance to reason through possible consequences and actions while still balanced
            - Strategy 2: separate the strands — feeling / story / feedback
                - Three questions, answered in sequence before moving to the next
                - What do I feel? Name the emotion; describe it physically — nausea, a jolt of adrenaline, something that feels like an electric shock, slightly faint
                - What's the story I'm telling? And inside the story, what is the threat?
                    - The threat could be about a bad thing that might happen, or about what this means for how others see you or how you see yourself
                    - Seth's story: "my boss disapproves of me; I'll lose this job; I mess up everything; I can't stand it; I'll just be unhappy all the time"
                - What was the actual feedback? The exact words, without the story added
                    - Seth's boss made one offhand comment about "everyone" being disorganized, including Seth; that is all
                    - Everything else was Seth's own addition
                - Our stories shadowbox with the past
                    - The "last straw" dynamic: each prior comment was weightless; this one is suddenly more than you can bear
                    - The neighbor complains about lawn maintenance; you snap; you've been told your whole life that you're slightly oblivious to social norms
                    - Open wounds: a colleague suggests speaking with more authority; you were bullied as a child, dismissed from the soccer team, broke up with by someone who said you never had opinions
                    - The current feedback is not the whole of what you're reacting to; that's okay and doesn't mean you're overreacting to the current feedback — it means the older material also needs attention
            - Strategy 3: contain the story
                - Three laws of physics for stories that strong feelings cause us to violate
                    - Time: the present does not change the past; the present influences but does not determine the future
                    - Specificity: being lousy at one thing does not make you lousy at unrelated things
                    - People: one person's view does not equal everyone's view; even they probably like some things about you; views can change over time
                - Feedback Containment Chart: two columns
                    - Left: what IS this feedback about?
                    - Right: what is it NOT about?
                    - Example: not getting your dream job is about whether you have the specific qualifications they were looking for; it is NOT about whether you will ever work in your chosen field or whether your future is determined by this outcome
                    - Writing the right column makes the trespass material visible and shrinks the feedback to its actual size
                - Balancing Picture: visual representation of proportions
                    - When you know logically you're over-weighting one negative comment in a set of positive feedback, but can't feel the proportion: draw it
                    - Alita draws the ratio of positive to negative patient feedback; she is shocked at how different the balance looks when rendered
                    - "Your drawing is not some final truth about the feedback. But seeing it in front of you, looking so different from how it feels, helps you loosen up your story."
                - Right-size the future consequences
                    - Distinguish between consequences that will happen and those that merely might
                    - In the grip of upsetting feedback, we process might-happen consequences as if they were will-happen
                    - Your boss confirmed you're not getting a raise. That your spouse will leave you because of the missing raise is only something that might happen.
                    - Underestimating resilience: the arthritis diagnosis that rules out swimming; you picture a gaping hole; but something will fill it — ten years ago the same thing happened with tennis, which led to swimming
                    - Daniel Gilbert: people consistently overestimate how awful they'll feel and how long they'll feel awful
            - Strategy 4: change your vantage point
                - Imagine you're an observer: give yourself the advice you'd give your sister in the same situation
                    - If Mom made that comment to your sister: "That one stupid comment is still bugging you? Why are you worrying about that? It meant nothing. That's how she is now, and anyway, you're an adult!"
                    - You have access to the same perspective — it requires deliberately stepping into it
                - Look back from the future: in ten or twenty or forty years, how significant will today's events look?
                    - You may still find the feedback challenging from that future vantage, but the forever bias becomes visibly false; the future-you has lived through this and continued
                - Cast the comedy: humor taps the left prefrontal cortex where amusement lives, disrupting the alarm signals
                    - The ability to laugh at yourself requires loosening your grip on your identity; aligning yourself with the world instead of trying to align the world to you
                    - Juliet, putting down her wine glass: "So boy meets girl. Boy deceives, betrays, and dumps girl. Girl will never date another bad boy because she has finally learned her lesson. Wait, who's that super-hot drummer over there?"
            - Strategy 5: accept that you can't control how others see you
                - Their views may be incomplete, outdated, unfair, or based on nothing
                - You can discuss, offer evidence, bring notarized statements from your therapist or the pope; you cannot make someone think differently about you
                - The football case: you love football for the chesslike strategy; your coworker insists it's adolescent compensation for insecure masculinity; you cannot make her think something different
                - Most people are too obsessed with themselves to be obsessed with you; your ex-spouse is probably watching Luke on America's Got Talent, not thinking about you
                - Others' views of you are input, not imprint: don't dismiss them unseen, but don't accept them wholesale either
                - Have compassion for them: remind yourself what their own history must look like; the wounds they are operating from; the patterns they learned before you appeared
        - Cultivating a growth identity
            - All-or-nothing identity as the structural vulnerability
                - Simple labels: "I'm competent," "I'm a good person," "I'm worthy of love" — all-or-nothing
                - Any feedback that suggests we are not "all" is heard as "nothing"
                - Two failure modes: deny the feedback to preserve the identity; or take it in with crippling exaggeration
                - Toggling between them: "If I accept this it means I'm a bad person. But that can't be right. I'm going to reject it. But why would they say it if it weren't true? On the other hand..." — flipping like a fish on the deck of a boat
                - The headline in The Daily Me: "Hardworking Academic" becomes "Fool Who Wasted Years Chasing Tenure"; "Good Son" becomes "Heartless Child Fails Mother"
            - Three things to accept about yourself
                - You will make mistakes: accepting this takes pressure off; mistakes happen to even brilliant, generous people; every given mistake can still shock and dismay you without being evidence of fundamental incompetence
                - Your intentions are complex: mixed in with your positive intentions are less noble ones; self-interest is a requirement of being alive; occasionally it will conflict with others' interests and occasionally that will be pointed out to you
                - You have contributed to the problem: the "I-don't-have-to-take-feedback-from-you-because-you-did-something-wrong-too club" just closes down the chance to learn and address the problem
            - Shift 1: give up simple labels and cultivate complexity
                - The narrator who placed their mother in a full-time care facility: not "good son" or "bad son" but someone who cares deeply about being a good son, has thousands of examples of living up to it, and some of falling short
                - "There are some things about how you handled the situation that you're proud of. And there are some things you are less proud of."
                - Rita's feedback ("this was selfish") can now be examined from a complex identity without destroying the whole self-story
                - "As your story of the situation and yourself becomes more nuanced, you wonder whether there is something to learn in Rita's view."
            - Shift 2: move from fixed mindset to growth mindset (Carol Dweck)
                - Fixed: traits and abilities are carved in stone; feedback is a verdict; every situation is a referendum on whether you have the smarts or ability you think you have
                - Growth: traits can develop; effort matters; feedback is information about where you are on a learning curve
                - Dweck's puzzles: some kids became more energized as the puzzles got harder; one boy licked his lips saying "I was hoping this would be informative!"
                    - The kids who gave up thought: "The first puzzles showed I was smart; these new ones make me look dumb"
                    - The kids who persisted thought: "These harder puzzles are helping me get better at doing puzzles. This is fun!"
                - The Testing Room vs. the Learning Room: which room would you rather live your life in?
                - EEG study at Columbia: fixed-mindset students paid close attention to whether they got it right or wrong, but lost interest when told what the right answer was; growth-mindset students listened closely to the right answers and outperformed on retesting
                - The fifth-graders study: praising effort ("you worked hard") produces willingness to take on challenges; praising intelligence ("you're so smart") produces risk avoidance
                    - Even among the half who had fixed-mindset assumptions, praising effort produced willingness to take on the next challenge; "working hard" is a trait they felt confident they could replicate
            - Practice 1: sort toward coaching
                - When feedback arrives, default to hearing it as coaching rather than evaluation
                - Identity is easily triggered by evaluation; it is far less threatened by coaching — almost like a free pass
                - Elsbeth at the presentation break: heard as evaluation = "am I boring? Am I not up to an audience this senior?"; heard as coaching = "I should have more coffee and make this next segment more interactive"
                - Sorting exercise: think of a real piece of feedback you received; first hear it as evaluation (what verdict?); then hear it as coaching (what could you learn?)
                    - Three discoveries from the exercise: you can usually hear most feedback either way with effort; the identity reaction is diminished or gone in the coaching frame; you'll notice your own oversort patterns
                - When coaching and evaluation are tangled, find the coaching at the core
                    - Lisa telling Margaret "when I was eight and Dad left, I felt like you had abandoned me too"
                    - Margaret hears "you were a bad mother" (evaluation); Lisa wants three things: to be understood, to receive acknowledgment that her mother's choices contributed to her pain, and to have a better current relationship (coaching)
                    - What would be most satisfying to Lisa? Not "okay, maybe I was a bad mother." But "I never realized how I was affecting you during that time. I'm so sorry."
            - Practice 2: unpack judgment from the evaluation suitcase
                - Break evaluation into three constituent parts
                    - Assessment: where do I stand? (The measurement itself — the mile time, the ranking)
                    - Consequences: what happens as a result? (Certain vs. speculative; immediate vs. long-term)
                    - Judgment: what story does the evaluator tell about the assessment and its consequences?
                - Identity is most triggered by judgment, not by assessment or consequences
                - Track meet: the assessment (5:19, fourth place in the age group) is acceptable; the consequences (regionals yes, nationals no) are manageable; the coach's disappointment is what hooks identity
                - Accurate assessment is valuable; consequences are important to understand; others' judgments are one interpretation, and you have your own
            - Practice 3: give yourself a second score
                - After any first score, earn a second score for how you handle it
                - The first score is for the situation itself; the second score is for what you do with it
                - You can receive an F for the situation and an A+ for the handling
                - Mel and Melinda: both got a thumbs-down on their first YouTube video
                    - Mel: angrily accused the world of being too stupid, withdrew
                    - Melinda: wondered what they could learn; weeks later noticed the jump cuts were too jumpy, the lyrics hard to make out; studied film editing; posted new videos; eventually reworked the original to a mostly positive reception
                - Make the second score part of your identity: "I don't always succeed, but I take an honest shot at figuring out what there is to learn from the failure. I'm actually pretty good at that."
                - Handling it well does not mean denying pain or emerging unscathed: Heather, whose longtime girlfriend left her: "All I had control over was my reaction, and I got up every morning and went to work. I treated everyone around me respectfully. Actually, working to 'handle it well' gave me something to focus on and to feel good about."

- Three kinds of feedback and their mismatches
    - Appreciation: you matter, your work matters, your effort is seen
        - Qualities of meaningful appreciation: specific; in a form the receiver can actually hear; authentic
        - Mutual appreciation deficit disorder (MADD): each party feels underappreciated despite both giving appreciation
        - Even authentic appreciation is not universal: what feels meaningful to you may not land for someone else
        - In workplaces: fewer people worry that they receive too much appreciation and far more worry they receive too little
    - Coaching: here is how to improve or change
        - The goal is to help the receiver learn or get better at something
        - Good coaching is specific and actionable: could you make a movie of "doing it differently"?
        - "Try it this way" contains the implicit message "so far, you haven't been doing it as well as you might" — evaluation is structurally inside coaching
    - Evaluation: here is where you stand
        - Tells you where you stand relative to expectations; ranks you; informs what comes next
        - The evaluative floor: evaluation is structurally loud and drowns out coaching and appreciation
        - You cannot absorb coaching until you know whether you are on solid ground — or not
        - Silent evaluation creates the same stuck state as loud unfavorable evaluation: you still don't know where you stand
    - Three mismatches that cause feedback to fail
        - Want vs. got: you wanted coaching; they gave evaluation — or the reverse
            - April wanted coaching on her presentation; Cody gave evaluation ("you're behind"); she couldn't hear any of it
            - Evelyn's case: she wanted appreciation; he gave coaching ("here's how to do it differently"); she heard it as more criticism
        - Intent vs. hearing: the evaluative echo inside coaching
            - Elsie hears evaluation inside coaching even when the giver intends pure coaching
            - "Have you considered doing X instead?" is heard as "you should have been doing X all along"
        - Mixed kinds arriving simultaneously
            - Appreciation, coaching, and evaluation all at once means none lands clearly
    - Sort the kind: name which kind is in play
        - Before soliciting feedback: name the kind you want
        - During the conversation: check what kind is being given vs. what kind you needed
        - If you're getting the wrong kind: "Can you first just tell me where I stand?"
        - Negotiate explicitly when necessary: "I think I'm hearing two different things from you. First I heard appreciation, and then I heard you give me feedback on how I could have done it differently. Can we be explicit about which one you're focused on?"
    - Settle evaluation first
        - The evaluative floor: silent evaluation creates the same stuck state as a loud unfavorable one
        - You cannot focus on coaching until the evaluation question is answered
        - The explicit move: "Before you give me your coaching, can you tell me how you think I'm doing? Am I on track?"
        - Sara's case: "I was being promoted awfully fast and it was making me nervous. I asked the partner before he started coaching. He said, 'Sara, you're doing great! You've definitely got a future here.' The minute he said it, I could relax and focus on his coaching."

- Setting limits on feedback
    - Being able to say no is right at the heart of receiving feedback well; if you can't say no, your yeses are not freely chosen
    - Your emotional acre: Anne Lamott's image — you get one; as long as you don't hurt anyone, you get to do with it as you please; there's a fence around it with a gate; if people keep sliming it, you get to ask them to leave
    - Three kinds of boundaries
        - I may not take your advice (softest: I'm listening but the choice is mine)
            - Sometimes you need to state this explicitly because the giver doesn't realize it's optional
            - The mother-in-law who gripes when you don't choose her florist: "Why do you even ask my advice if you don't care what I say?"
        - I don't want feedback about that subject right now
            - Your sister has badgered you to quit smoking for years; with an uncle dying of a smoking-related illness, the whole family has joined the chorus; you need them to back off
        - Stop, or I will leave the relationship (starkest)
            - Simply being in the relationship while buffeted by ongoing judgment is doing damage to your sense of self
    - Six diagnostic questions for when a boundary is needed
        - Do they attack your character, not just your behavior? ("Here's what's wrong with you" vs. "here's an idea that would help")
        - Is the feedback unrelenting even after you've asked them to stop? (Unhelpful feedback is useless; relentless unhelpful feedback is destructive)
        - When you do change, is there always one more demand? (The act of controlling may be the end in itself)
        - Does the giver take the relationship hostage? ("If you don't take my feedback it means you don't love me" — ties something small to something big)
        - Are they issuing threats rather than warnings? (Warning = communicating legitimate consequences so you can make informed choices; threat = manufacturing consequences to induce fear or dependence or lower self-esteem)
        - Is it always you who has to change? (If you are always the one who absorbs the budget overruns and apologizes, the roles may be stuck)
        - Are your views and feelings a legitimate part of the relationship? (Regardless of anything else: does the giver listen to you and work to understand how you see things?)
    - Henry and Isabella: the renovation relationship
        - She started with wardrobe suggestions; he figured it wouldn't hurt to be a sharper dresser
        - The feedback spread: work out more, stop reading those comics, don't act like such a nerd in front of my friends, don't take things so personally, have some ambition, make my hobbies your hobbies
        - Henry told Isabella how unhappy he was; she explained he was just too sensitive to feedback
        - Rollo's diagnosis: "It sounds as if she's trying to turn you into someone else. But even putting that aside, it sounds like your feelings are not part of the equation, and what you need is not part of the relationship. That's a giant red flag."
        - Henry has become so preoccupied by whether he can please Isabella that he isn't noticing how little his needs and feelings matter to her
    - Setting the boundary clearly
        - Be transparent: actually tell them out loud (Dave needed a hearing aid; told no one; coworkers thought he was dismissing them)
            - "I got checked. I need a hearing aid. I'm going to get one. It's a hard adjustment. I'll do better if I'm not pestered."
        - Be firm and appreciative simultaneously: PJ and her department head
            - "When you say 'don't be nervous' I know you're trying to help. The impact, though, is it actually makes me more nervous. What would help me is to hear how you've been able to cope with anxiety when you speak publicly — but I'd like to hear about that on days when I'm not lecturing."
        - Redirect the coaching energy: "You might experiment with loaning your giver a corner of your acre, and tell them what you'd love to see there"
            - Hunyee to her mother: "I have so much to learn from you. When you visit, would you teach me to make your amazing dumplings?"
        - Use "and" not "but"
            - "I love seeing you, but if you're going to come to my house you need to stop criticizing everything" — the "but" suggests the first part would be true, but for the second
            - Human emotions don't necessarily cancel each other out; "I love seeing you AND your comments about my weight need to stop" holds both truths simultaneously
            - Raul's ands with his parents: "I've been afraid to talk to you about this and it's important to me to be honest. I've decided to major in music and I know this makes you worry. I'm also very fearful of the struggle I may face and I need to try."
        - Be specific: three things to name
            - The Request: what exactly are you asking? What topic, what behavior?
            - The Time Frame: how long is the boundary likely to be in place?
            - Their Assent: ask explicitly whether they can honor the request; when they say yes, their identity is enlisted in keeping the promise
        - Describe consequences as warnings, not threats
            - "You know I've struggled with smoking. Right now I'm overwhelmed with my new job and I can't handle the side comments. If you can't leave the issue behind for now, I'll make sure to visit Marv at times when I know you won't be here."
    - Duty to mitigate when you decide not to change
        - Ask about and acknowledge the impact on others: Larry and his ADHD medication decision; his family and crew need to be in that conversation
        - Coach them to deal with the unchanged you: Jackie tells her teammates "I know I can be overbearing. I tried to change. So I give you all permission to cut me off. Red-card me. I don't mean to dominate discussions but I imagine I'll continue to do it without realizing it."
        - Problem-solve together: Mark and Steve's Steelers ticket protocol — assuming Steve isn't going to change, they discuss specific details about whether he can make it and what Mark needs if Steve bails; sometimes Steve suggests they go golfing instead, recognizing Mark is really asking so they can spend time together

- Getting going: acting on feedback
    - Name one thing
        - Willpower to change is a limited resource; trying to work on everything simultaneously exhausts it
        - The cookie-and-radish study: subjects asked to resist cookies (and eat radishes) gave up on geometry problems twice as quickly, after about half the attempts
        - Don't say "give me some feedback"; say "what's one thing you see me doing that gets in my own way?"
            - Grants permission to be candid
            - Narrows to behavior with observable impact
        - If you receive ten concerns: acknowledge and validate them all, then set priorities: "I'm serious about improving, and the best way for me to do that is to focus on one thing at a time. Let's figure out a good place for me to start."
        - Listen for themes: Rodrigo went to five people (three close collaborators, his boss, and a coworker he found irritating)
            - Three of five said the same thing: he hung back when he should have weighed in with direction
            - Until then, he had thought he was giving the team too little input and working hard at inclusiveness; in fact they needed more direction
            - His one thing for the next month: speak up and provide more direction; one colleague offered: "be willing to go a little overboard — if you do, I'll tell you"
        - Ask what matters to them: "What's one thing I could change that would make a difference to you?"
            - Sharon asked her three sons at dinner; eight-year-old Aidan yelled "more Skittles"; ten-year-old Colin said "we never go bowling anymore"
            - Not about bowling: "It's the only time the four of us ever do anything together, with just us, and we haven't done it for a year." Sharon called the alley and reserved a lane.
    - Try small experiments
        - In any contest between change and the status quo, the status quo has home field advantage
        - Reframe from all-and-always to some-and-sometimes: not "should I change my workshops forever?" but "try it one night"
        - Try it on (mental experiment): inhabit the possibility that the feedback is true; if it doesn't fit after a genuine attempt, take it off
            - Harpreet: student called him arrogant and condescending; his department head said "try it on — assume the student is on to something"
            - He tried it on; after considering from different angles, he began to see what the student might have meant; this proved enormously valuable for the rest of his career
            - "He would not have had access to it if he hadn't taken a genuine run at trying it on as true"
        - Try it out (real-world experiment)
            - Emily's five-year resistance to cutting her twenty-minute introduction; the feedback from coworkers, guest speakers, and parents kept coming
            - She finally tried it for one night; found awkward moments, found parts she wanted to retain, discovered five minutes plus a handout at the end worked better than twenty minutes and nothing
            - "It's not all-and-always. Just some-and-sometimes."
            - Gawande hired a surgical coach not because he knew he needed one, but because the downside seemed small and the upside worth exploring; complication rates went down; what he learned he couldn't have anticipated
    - Ride out the J curve
        - When implementing any change, things typically get worse before they get better
        - From inside the dip you can't tell whether you're at the bottom of the J about to rise or heading further down
        - The two-decision-maker problem: Sunday Night self makes commitments; Monday Morning self arrives and faces a different cost structure
        - Increase the positive appeal of change
            - Make it social: less unpleasant; adds accountability; provides appreciation; online communities work for introverts who don't want to buddy up in person
            - Keep score: turns behavior change into a game; Miyamoto's Wii Fit; Antoine and the science leaderboard ("Now I have to pass him — just to keep my honor")
        - Increase the cost of not changing: tie yourself to the mast (Odysseus)
            - Schelling stopped smoking by threatening himself with a donation to an organization he found morally repugnant
            - Doctors with drug addictions: confessional letters to the medical board, sealed, given to a friend to mail if they relapse — one more hit isn't just one more hit; it's their license, their career, their reputation
        - Commit to a specific duration that reaches past the dip
        - Bernardus and the online database: first few weeks a minor disaster; he lost data; it took longer than handwritten notes; he kept score of customers successfully entered; miss percentage slowly improved; six months later he takes notes directly in the database during customer calls and enjoys having all the information accessible
    - Coach your coach
        - Tell the person giving you feedback how to work with you more effectively
        - Your footprint, your current growth areas, what helps you hear things, what creates interference
        - "Subtle doesn't work with me. Be really explicit and don't worry about hurting my feelings."
        - "I tend to get defensive at first, and then I circle back later and figure out why the feedback is helpful. If I seem defensive, don't be put off."
        - "I react better when you present your advice as an idea that might help, rather than as the obviously right answer."
        - For formal coaching relationships: discuss preferences, roles, mutual expectations; ask what they find challenging about coaching you
        - In hierarchy: frame in terms of current-job effectiveness rather than ambition; "feedback on running meetings is important to me because I want to use the team's time as efficiently as I can, given the upcoming merger"
        - Workers who seek out negative feedback — coaching on what they can improve — tend to receive higher performance ratings
        - Don't become a feedback fanatic: earnest thirst for improving becomes burdensome when it's too frequent; try asking about their thoughts and experiences too
    - Invite them in
        - Letting someone far enough into your life to help you transforms the relationship; you become someone humble, vulnerable, and confident enough to ask for help; they become someone respected enough to be asked
        - Roseanne: she noticed all her conversations were about other people's problems; she learned she was sending signals she wasn't aware of — waving people off; she decided to learn to ask for help; she started with something she was lousy at but which wasn't crucial (her wardrobe); "Apparently, one way to get feedback is to ask"
        - Clay and Nadine: he held his tongue because she never seemed open to his ideas about her son; he finally asked her for advice on his own depression; she then started talking about Bryan; "I had suspected he'd struggled with depression and felt like I knew things that would help him, but always thought he was uncomfortable talking about it. So she was having the same experience I was of feeling uninvited to offer help."
        - Shifting mirrors: ask your supportive mirror to shift to honest mirror mode
            - Amy and Hank: she vented about Ivan; Hank listened and said "yeah" and "wow"; later Amy called back: "I need you to help me with that — I need you to help me understand what's going on with Ivan"
            - Hank's honest read: Amy has a pattern of needing to have the last word; it showed up in the text exchange during the conference call, and in the call with Hank at the end
            - Two-column technique: what's wrong with the feedback / what might be right or helpful
            - "Writing down and discussing what's wrong frees Amy to see what might be right or valid or reasonable"

- The feedback conversation itself
    - Open: get aligned before engaging with content
        - Is this feedback? If so, what kind? (The birthday sweater might be a mistake — or a message)
        - Who decides? (Some conversations need consensus; others have a clear decision-maker; some don't need agreement at all)
        - Is this final or negotiable? (Don't invest energy trying to change what is already decided; focus on understanding and handling consequences)
        - You can influence the frame and agenda regardless of how the other person started
            - "Can we take a minute to step back so that I'm clear on our purposes? I want to be sure I'm on the same page as you."
        - MIT research: correlation between skilled interaction during the first five minutes and good outcomes
        - Gottman: if the first three minutes of a fifteen-minute conversation are harsh and not corrected, the outcome is negative 96% of the time; happy marriages show ability to make and respond to "repair attempts"
    - Body: four skills
        - Listening
            - Your internal voice is like a personal assistant whose job is to make sure no one bothers you; when triggered, it becomes an armed bodyguard
            - Mirror neuron research: Tania Singer's fMRI studies show we feel others' pain when we observe it — but only for those we believe are behaving well; when we feel unfairly treated, empathy may be neurologically turned off
            - What helps: listen with a purpose; instead of wrong-spotting, listen for what's right and be curious about why you see things so differently
            - Prepare to listen: have a conversation with your internal voice before the feedback conversation
                - Identify your trigger patterns; then negotiate toward curiosity
                - "I suppose they could see things we don't see. That's been known to happen. And their interpretation may be different, but it could be valid. Also, they've been around the block a few times. There's that."
            - Listening's second purpose: to let them know you hear them; they can't argue you didn't take the advice seriously; they'll be more likely to listen to you explain where you ultimately land
            - Beware hot inquiry: questions in punctuation only, heated by the affront you're struggling to contain ("Do you actually believe that?" "Why are you so stupid?")
                - These are assertions, not questions; the intention is to persuade or attack, not to learn
                - If overwhelmed, don't try to fight through it and inquire; assert; replace hot inquiry with a thoughtful assertion
        - Asserting
            - Feedback is not simply a thing the giver hands you; the two of you are building a puzzle; when you don't assert, you withhold your pieces
            - From truth asserting to difference asserting: "I disagree with that advice" rather than "that advice is wrong"
            - "We had a different approach in the last place I worked, and we had fewer problems. The giver doesn't know what succeeded at my last job; I don't know what they have tried in the past here. That's the conversation to have."
            - Common assertion mistakes by trigger type
                - Truth mistakes: "That advice is wrong" → "I disagree with that advice"
                - Relationship mistakes: "You're a self-centered jerk" → "I'm feeling underappreciated, so it's hard for me to focus on your feedback; I think we need to discuss both"
                - Systems mistakes: "This is not my fault" → "I agree there are things I've contributed. I'd also like to step back to look at the bigger picture together."
                - Identity mistakes: "It's true, I'm hopeless" → "I'm surprised by all this and it's a lot to take in. I want to take some time to think about it. Let's come back to it tomorrow."
        - Process moves
            - Step outside the conversation's content; diagnose what is stuck; describe it explicitly; propose a correction
            - "We're both making arguments, trying to persuade the other, but I don't think either of us is listening. Tell me more about why this is so important to you."
            - "I see two issues here, and we're jumping back and forth between them. Let's focus on one at a time."
            - "I'm not saying my view is right and yours is wrong. I'm saying we see it differently. I wonder if there are aspects of how you see this that I'm not fully understanding?"
            - "I'm shocked by this. I'd like to take a break and come back in a couple of hours after we've both had time to calm down."
            - All of these sound slightly awkward — not how regular people talk; the awkwardness signals that you are stepping outside the flow to examine the process
        - Problem-solving
            - Gathering information and testing perceptions
            - Creating options that would meet both sides' primary concerns
            - Where you can't agree, trying to find fair ways to resolve the difference
            - Dig for underlying interests: Alita's patients want to understand why appointments run late and each still wants attentiveness when their time comes; a sign in the waiting room actually meets some of those real concerns
            - Earl's case: supervisor's position = "clean up your appearance"; underlying interest = "we want families to feel comfortable with you more quickly"; Earl addressed the interest by asking his supervisor to describe him as a semiprofessional bluegrass banjo player before meetings with new families
            - Three buckets for interests behind feedback: helping you; helping themselves and the relationship; helping the organization, team, or someone else
    - Close: commit
        - Name what was agreed and what each party will do next
        - Can commit to gathering more information, returning to the conversation, or stating which parts you won't take and why
        - Feedback conversations are rarely one-shot deals; they are a series of conversations over time
        - Signposting where you stand and what you'll try next helps you travel the road together
